{{italic title}}
{{Augustine}}
The '''''Harmony of the Gospels''''' ({{lang-la|De consensu evangeliorum}}) is a book by the 5th-century saint, [[Augustine of Hippo]].<ref name=Lancel >''Augustine through the ages: an encyclopedia'' by John C. Cavadini, 1999, {{ISBN|0-8028-3843-X}}, p. 132</ref>

In the book (which has four separate parts) Augustine assumes that [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] was the first Gospel, followed by Mark and Luke and that John was the last. He then analyzes and relates the specific passages between the Gospels, to build a [[Gospel harmony]].

In the book Augustine views the variations in the gospel accounts in terms of the different focuses of the authors on Jesus: Matthew on royalty, Mark on humanity, Luke on priesthood and John on divinity.<ref name=Tuckett38 >''Christology, Controversy and Community'' by David G. Horell and Christopher M. Tuckett, 2000, {{ISBN|9004116796}}, pp. 37–40</ref>

