[[File:Jozef Goluchowski.jpg|thumb|200px|Józef Gołuchowski. Portrait by [[Maksymilian Fajans]].]] '''Józef Gołuchowski''' (1797–1858) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[philosopher]].<ref name=Goluchowski/>
Gołuchowski, a professor at [[Vilnius University]], was co-creator of the [[Romanticism in Poland|Polish Romanticist]] "national philosophy." He preached the concept of the [[nation]] as a creation of [[God]], with a peculiar "national spirit," that realized the ideal of a hierarchical society in which each individual is a necessary fragment of the whole. He opposed 18th-century materialist philosophy from an irrationalist position. In the [[theory of knowledge]], he preached the primacy of feeling and [[Intuition (knowledge)|intuition]] over [[reason]].<ref name=Goluchowski/>
==See also== *[[History of philosophy in Poland#Messianism|History of philosophy in Poland]] *[[List of Poles#Philosophy|List of Poles]]
