{{Redirect|Glib|the software library|GLib}} {{For|other uses of the word "charm"|Charm (disambiguation)}}
'''Superficial charm''' (or '''insincere charm''' or '''glib charm''') is the tendency to be smooth, engaging, charming, slick and verbally facile.<ref>Hare's checklist, as cited in {{cite book |title=Psychopathy: antisocial, criminal, and violent behavior |authorlink=Theodore Millon |first=Theodore |last=Millon |first2=Erik |last2=Simonsen |first3=Morten |last3=Birket-Smith |first4=Roger D. |last4=Davis |location=New York |publisher=Guilford Press |year=2002 |page=173 |isbn=1-57230-344-1 }}</ref>
The phrase often appears in lists of attributes of [[psychopath]]ic personalities, such as in [[Hervey M. Cleckley]]'s ''[[The Mask of Sanity]]'',<ref>{{cite book | last=Cleckley | first=Hervey | accessdate= 14 November 2009 | url= http://www.cassiopaea.org/cass/sanity_1.PdF | title = The Mask of Sanity | publisher = Emily S. Cleckley | edition= 5th | year=1988 | isbn= 0-9621519-0-4}}</ref> and [[Robert D. Hare]]'s [[Hare Psychopathy Checklist]].<ref>Hare, Robert D. (1991). "The Hare Psychopathy Checklist" (Revised). (North Tonawanda, NY: Multi-Health Systems)</ref>
Associated expressions are "[[#Charm offensive|charm offensive]]", "turning on the charm" and "[[Superficiality|superficial]] [[smile]]".
== Early history == [[Classical rhetoric]] had early singled out the critical category of the superficial charmer, whose merit was purely verbal, without underlying substance.<ref>{{cite book |first=M. L. |last=Clarke |first2=D. H. |last2=Berry |title=Rhetoric at Rome: A Historical Survey |year=1996 |location=New York |publisher=Routledge |page=146 |isbn=0-415-14155-9 |edition=Rev. }}</ref>
== Psychopathic charm == Contemporary interest in superficial charm goes back to [[Hervey M. Cleckley]]'s classic study (1941) of the sociopath: since his work it has become widely accepted that the sociopath/psychopath was characterised by superficial charm and a disregard for other people's feelings.<ref>{{cite book |first=Bella |last=DePaulo |first2=Leah |last2=Wilson |title=The Psychology of Dexter |location=Dallas |publisher=Smart Pop |year=2010 |page=7 |isbn=978-1-935251-97-2 }}</ref> According to Hare, "Psychopathic charm is not in the least shy, self-conscious, or afraid to say anything."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/zine2/narcissism/psychopathy_checklist.html |title=Antisocial Personality, Sociopathy, and Psychopathy |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818085421/http://www.angelfire.com/zine2/narcissism/psychopathy_checklist.html |archivedate=2010-08-18 |df= }}</ref>
Subsequent studies have refined, but not perhaps fundamentally altered, Cleckley's initial assessment. In the latest diagnostic review, Cleckley's mix of intelligence and superficial charm has been redefined to reflect a more deviant demeanour, talkative, slick, and insincere.<ref>{{cite book |first=R. F. |last=Salekin |first2=D. R. |last2=Lynam |title=Handbook of Child and Adolescent Psychopathology |year=2010 |location=New York |publisher=Guilford Press |page=22 |isbn=978-1-60623-682-6 }}</ref> A distinction can also be drawn between a subtle, self-effacing kind of sociopathic charm,<ref>Jon Ronson, ''[[The Psychopath Test]]'' (2011) p. 143.</ref> and a more expansive, exhilarating spontaneity which serves to give the sociopath a sort of animal magnetism.<ref>Martha Stout, ''The Sociopath Next Door'' (2005) pp. 88–89.</ref>
=== Workplace === {{Main|Psychopathy in the workplace}}
The authors of the book [[Snakes in Suits: When Psychopaths Go to Work]] describe a five phase model of how a typical workplace [[psychopath]] climbs to and maintains [[Power (social and political)|power]]. In phase one (entry), the psychopath will use highly developed [[social skills]] and charm to obtain employment by an organisation.<ref name=Snakes>Baibak, P; [[Robert D. Hare|Hare, R. D]] [[Snakes in Suits: When Psychopaths Go to Work]] (2007)</ref> Corporate psychopaths within organizations may be singled out for rapid promotion because of their polish, charm, and cool decisiveness.<ref name=Financial>Boddy, C. R The Corporate Psychopaths Theory of the Global Financial Crisis Journal of Business Ethics August 2011, Volume 102, Issue 2, pp 255-259</ref> Their superficial charm may be misinterpreted as charisma.<ref name=Snakes/><ref name=fbi>https://leb.fbi.gov/2012/november/the-corporate-psychopath </ref>
== Narcissism == {{Main|Narcissism}}
The term also occurs in Hotchkiss' discussion of narcissists: "Their superficial charm can be enchanting."<ref>{{cite book |last=Hotchkiss |first=Sandy |authorlink2=James F. Masterson |last2=Masterson |first2=James F. |title=Why Is It Always About You? : The Seven Deadly Sins of Narcissism |year=2003 |location=New York |publisher=Free Press |isbn=0-7432-1428-5 }}</ref> For such figures, however, there is no substance behind the romantic gestures, which only serve to feed the narcissist's own ego.<ref>{{cite book |first=Simon |last=Crompton |title=All about Me: Loving a Narcissist |location=London |publisher=Collins |year=2007 |pages=68–69 |isbn=978-0-00-724795-0 }}</ref>
Narcissists are known as [[Psychological manipulation|manipulative]] in a charming way, entrapping their victims through a [[façade]] of understanding into suspending their self-protective behaviour and lowering their [[personal boundaries]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Alexander |last=Abdennur |title=Camouflaged Aggression: The Hidden Threat to Individuals and Organizations |year=2000 |pages=87 and 156 |location=Calgary |publisher=Detselig |isbn=1-55059-198-3 }}</ref> Closely related is the way [[impostor]]s are able to make people fall in love with them to satisfy their narcissistic needs, without reciprocating in any real sense or returning their feelings.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Otto Fenichel |first=Otto |last=Fenichel |title=The Psychoanalytic Theory of Neurosis |location=London |publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul |year=1946 |page=374 }}</ref>
== Social chameleons ==
Social [[chameleons]] have been described as adept in [[social intelligence]], able to make a charming good impression, yet at the price of their own true motivations.<ref>[[Daniel Goleman]], ''Emotional Intelligence'' (London 1996) pp. 118–119.</ref> Their ability to manage impressions well often leads to success in areas like the theatre, salesmanship, or politics and diplomacy.<ref>Goleman, p. 120.</ref> But when lacking a sense of their own inner needs, such superficial [[extravert]]s may end up (despite their charm) as rootless chameleons, endlessly taking their social cues from other people.<ref>Goleman, pp. 119–120.</ref>
Similarly, for the [[Histrionic personality disorder|histrionic personality]], the [[attention seeking]] through superficial charm may only reinforce the [[Splitting (psychology)|splitting]] of the [[True self and false self|real self]] from the public presentation in a vicious circle.<ref>Len Sperry, ''Handbook of diagnosis and treatment of DSM-IV-TR personality disorder'' (2003) p. 138.</ref>
== Positive outcomes ==
Superficial charmers, in their more benign manifestations, can produce a variety of positive results, their conversational skills providing light-hearted entertainment in social settings through their ability to please.<ref>Salekin, p. 414.</ref>
== Charm offensive == {{See also|Public relations|Spin (public relations)}}
A "charm offensive" is a related concept meaning a publicity campaign, usually by politicians, that attempts to attract supporters by emphasizing their charisma or [[trustworthiness]]. The first recorded use of the expression is in the California newspaper ''[[The Fresno Bee Republican]]'' in October 1956.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin, Gary |url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/89950.html |title=Charm offensive |work=The Phrase Finder|date= |accessdate=2013-06-15}}</ref>
== Literary analogues == [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] explored the destructive consequences of excess charm in stories like "Magnetism", maintaining that charm, for those who had it, had a life of its own, demanding constant use to keep it in peak condition.<ref>[[F. Scott Fitzgerald]], ''Bernice Bobs Her Hair and other stories'' (Penguin 1968) p. 149.</ref>
==Criticism== Critics object that there are few objective criteria whereby to distinguish superficial from genuine charm; and that as part of the conventional niceties of politeness, we all regularly employ superficial charm in everyday life:<ref>S. J. Pfohl, ''Images of Deviance and Social Control'' (1985) p. 103.</ref> conveying superficial solidarity and fictitious benevolence to all social interactions.<ref>Steven Pinker, ''The Stuff of Thought'' (2007) pp. 480–481.</ref>
